URL reference: https://medium.com/@c0gnit00/kubernetes-and-k3s-a-practical-deep-dive-27051aaec45e
DateReviewed: 2026-07-11
Description: So today we're going to look at Kubernetes and the K3s distro it seems. This article starts from first principles, explaining what K8s is to start. Then it moves on to how the cluster works from the big picture perspective, talking about the components of the system. They use K3s as an example (showing some typical K3s pods). After they run through the data plane, they pivot to the control plane, which runs it all. So, we get a full walkthrough of K8s, before we get to lightweight K8s - K3s. The idea is to have something small and mostly self contained, which for K3s means a 70MB binary for the cluster components in total. So while it looks like standard K8s, it's slimmer under the hood - sqlite instead of etcd, for instance. They explain some challenges of this approach, and dive into K8s RBAC and how that works, with some CLI bits. It then goes through the "key" ports that K3s supports, and what they do. They talk about ServiceAccount tokens, so you know how they work. Then there is a command ref and some small tutorials on how to do stuff. Very well done.
BottomLine: Good piece on K3s and how things work overall in Kubernetes
