URL reference: https://itnext.io/configuration-as-code-is-a-liability-for-security-d0e53727cd17
DateReviewed: 2026-07-12
Description: Today's article is going to talk about configuration as code, and why this might be a vulnerability. They start with example questions, like across all namespaces and clusters, where am I missing a default deny Network Policy. Their claim is when using ConfAsCode, you can't query a single place to answer (as the configs might be in different spots/repos). They point out you can run against your live clusters, but if you find an issue then you still have to track the config repo (or drift and patch live). They pose another option - using ConfigHub, which treats config as data. Now, it might be a great tool, and they do give some detail on deploying and using it, but it seems like a radical departure from current practices, and I'm not sure all use cases are covered. It's an interesting take to read, though.
BottomLine: Alternative system for doing configuration as code on Kubernetes
